I&#39;m creating a framework to test XML responses to our system.  Right now I
have a properties file that contains 1) every file request I want to send to
our system and 2) the xpath expressions I want to run on the XML response,
to make sure it&#39;s correct.  The properties file looks like this:

&lt;xml_testing controldir=&quot;controlxml&quot; requestdir=&quot;requestxml&quot;&gt;
   &lt;file name=&quot;test1.xml&quot;&gt;
      &lt;xpath expression=&quot;//FUNCTION/RESPONSE_DATA&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;xpath expression=&quot;//USER&quot;/&gt;
   &lt;/file&gt;
   &lt;file name=&quot;test2.xml&quot;&gt;
      &lt;xpath expression=&quot;//HEADER/IP_ADDRESS&quot;/&gt;
   &lt;/file&gt;
   &lt;file name=&quot;test3.xml&quot;&gt;
      &lt;xpath expression=&quot;//USER/NAME&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;xpath expression=&quot;//USER/ADDRESS&quot;/&gt;
   &lt;/file&gt;
&lt;/xml_testing&gt;

The problem I&#39;m having is that I want each &lt;file&gt; to run as a separate test
in the JUnit framework.  Right now, even if I have 100 files that I want to
test in my properties file, the JUnit framework treats it all as one test.
I don&#39;t want test #4 to fail and then prevent the other 96 tests from
running, which is what&#39;s happening now.  Any ideas?  Thanks.



